Paul and Tom,<br><br>
Good questions, all.  But I maintain that we had a function there, and had we found the political will, could have made for a different outcome.  <br><br>
In 1971 I was part of a rescue force stationed at Bein Hoa.  Our primary mission was not to rescue in S. Vietnam, but to evacuate the US Embasy in Phnom Penh, Combodia.  The two wars were connected, and had common support from North Vietnam.  We felt that the Cambodian capitol would fall in that year.  It did not until well after we left.  I have said it before on these threads...it is my belief that we prevented the holocaust in Cambodia for about ten years.  <br><br>
You guys can say what you want, but I know that most of those who served in Vietnam had an impact in preventing some very nasty consequences of the Communist's takeover in those countries involved.  I will not say that those who died there did so in vain.  <br><br>
For those who protested, I have a question.  What did you say to those Vietnamese students in your university when S. Vietnam fell?  What my room mate and I did was to put one up in our apartment when he had no other support, no money, no means of communications with his home, his family and his nation.
